<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the Environment Bank to the Environment Audit Committee on the Defra Green paper on biodiversity offsetti</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> the Environment Bank </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> &amp; declaration of interest</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Environment Bank is a private </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sector company set up</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to facilitate biodiversity offsetting for the benefit of the environment, developers and planning authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; as such, we have a clear interest in a successful biodiversity offsetting scheme for England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  In offsetting parlance the Environment Bank is both:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a ‘broker’ - we seek to provide developers who wish to purchase offset credits with the right number of credits, of the right type, in the right place, at the right price, so that they are able to discharge their environmental obligations and secure planning permission, and </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a ‘delivery assurer’ – we provide the fiscal and legal mechanisms to assure Local Planning Authorities that long-term delivery of the biodiversity gain is guaranteed, so that they can be confident that the their planning decision will deliver net biodiversity gain.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Environment Bank was founded in 2008 and initiated and led early discussion</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the UK on both offsetting and habitat banking. Our staff, some of whom have direct experience of international offsetting programs, work with and for Local Planning Authorities; our Chief Executive is a former Government Agency Chief Scientist.  The Environment Bank is not a ‘bank’ in the sense of either commercial financing or habitat banking. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Environment Bank are formal partners with local planning authorities in two of the six Defra offsetting pilots, are working closely with several other planning authorities outside of the pilots, and have a national registry with nearly 100 potential offset receptor sites. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further details on who we are and what we do may be found on our website: </span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.environmentbank.com</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Environment Bank strongly supports the principle of biodiversity offsetting, and welcomes the Defra Green Paper. We believe that biodiversity offsetting is an essential planning tool – and a key mechanism in transforming the current ‘lose-lose’ of the existing planning system, whereby in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">variably the environment is destroyed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at great expense to developers, into a ‘win-win’ option for both the environment and developers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We hope to inform the EAC inquiry questions – Is the Defra consultation adequate? Does it deal with the real issues? – by reference to four separate areas:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Making the case for offsetting – the overarching principles</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Choosing an offsetting system - evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from the pilots and IA</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Intelligent design – enabling not prescribing</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Options for species offsetting</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Making the case for offsetting</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-indent:-49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Biodiversity offsetting is a relatively complex and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">novel mechanism, with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">varying levels of support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and understanding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from both conservationists and developers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at present</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  In this context, as major supporters of offsetting, we believe the Green Paper could have made a more compelling case for introducing biodiversity offsetting.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We consider that the case for change to the existing system is clear and evidenced; for example:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> own research</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> demonstrates that biodiversity was considered as material in only 1% of 10,235 applications; even where it was considered material it was rarely a reason for refusal; then, where mitigation or compensation was considered appropriate it was rarely delivered effectively.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2007/8 the £98 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> construction industry incurred £4.9bn s106 obligations, but only £5m went on nature conservation schemes</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – in other words, environmental reparation is currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">considered to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">worth only one thousandth of the overall impact of development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Numerous ‘State of the Environment’ reports strongly evidence environmental loss in England</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – for instance, 500 species have gone extinct in the past 200 years, 60% of all species are declining across all major </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">taxa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – nature conservation in this country, including through the planning system, is not working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Developers were constantly frustrated by delays to their planning permission driven by species-based cons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ervation issues, with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">million</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s of pounds lost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through extending </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> times and reduced net developable areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> impact assessment suggests 0.5% of developable land could be freed at a saving of £20m – we believe this could be an underestimate by an order of magnitude (closer to 5% and £200m per annum)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Conversely, the case for biodiversity offsetting is well-evidenced through international and national experience; offsetting will deliver:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£57m savings to businesses through improved planning</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">80% reduction in habitat loss</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consistent and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rigorous but transparent, fair and accountable treatment of environmental loss</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">externalization of the cost of biodiversity loss into the planning system</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mainstreaming of biodiversity restoration and creation projects into British agriculture, with concomitant diversification of income and resilience opportunities for farmers</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increased business opportunities for support sectors (such as brokers, impact assessors, management plan experts and monitoring systems)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">new funding of in excess of £400M pa to conservation projects, with the potential for large-scale and long-term planning.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:21.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are a number of legitimate concerns about how offsetting will work in practice, which deserve careful consideration and resolution, but the Government Green Paper should better set out the imperative need for reform of the planning system, and the advantages of offsetting.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We support the Green Paper objectives for offsetting – improved planning system, improved biodiversity conservation, avoiding additional costs – and believe there is ample evidence to be confident of delivery success.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Choosing an offsetting system</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:29.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Green Paper sets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> out four options for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> offsetting:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Fully permissive – developers choose if and how</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Partially permissive – developers must apply metric but choose compensation option</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Uniform (mandatory) – developers required to offset (possibly with a threshold level that triggers offsetting)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Community Infrastructure Levy – offsets funded by planning authority levies.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Empirical evidence from the UK and internationally</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> suggests that options 1 and 4 are likely to be highly ineffective, whilst option 3 would be most effective.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government offsetting pilots – deployed using a fully permissive approach – were presumably designed to test this option. The results are stark, with not one single offsetting scheme delivered after 18 months.  Partially this is due to the very slow pace of the planning system, but mainly it is because very few developers will ever choose to compensate where they are not required to do so.  Lack of demand then fails to drive offset supply, the market stays small and expensive, and the system does not work. Under voluntary systems none of the stakeholders learn how the process works, developers object to being asked to offset in one place where competitors are not being made to elsewhere, and fiscal, legal and supply side processes do not develop.  If there is one key lesson to draw from the Government pilots it is that a fully permissive system will not work.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Delivery through the Community Infrastructure Levy would be problematic on two counts. Firstly, as evidenced by the s106 data referenced above, funds for the environment are rarely spent on the environment unless they are ring-fenced – this is generally because environmental projects are difficult to cost and deliver and their benefits are difficult to quantify.  Secondly, funding through levy substantiates developers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fears that offsetting is “just another Green tax”. In fact, offsetting funding is not a tax (on profit)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it is a specific and attributable cost (of development) – and the externalization of paying for the reparation of environmental damage (with the funding of specific environmental projects) as a real cost to society, one that must be quantified and borne, is critical to new environmental paradigms. CIL is therefore both inappropriate and ineffective for delivering an offsetting system.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A ‘uniform’ approach will be most effective in delivering offsetting; uniform approaches will:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 55.06pt; padding-left:15.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Assure developers that they are being treated consistently across the country</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Enable planning authorities to make long-term decisions about offsetting delivery</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Allow offset suppliers to make long-term decisions about land management</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Increase market efficiencies and reduce overall costs</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Enable habitat banks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(areas of land set aside for conservation management to deliver offset credits) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to scale up both spatially and temporally</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Defra Impact A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssessment discusses (p20) three types of business saving to developers from offsetting – improved negotiating over compensation, increased net developable area on-site, and unblocking development. Even with very conservative estimates of the impact of these, Defra estimate a direct benefit of £57m pa from a uniform approach. Greatest business savings will come from the most widespread deployment of offsetting, and economies of scale will also be most effective under uniform approaches, so it is not clear to us why the business savings are not greatest in the uniform approach of the Impact Assessment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The use of thresholds, so that offsetting is triggered for only the largest developments, thereby avoiding increased burden on small developments seems reasonable – we note that a threshold of 10 houses would limit application of the offsetting metrics to just 10% of the planning applications but cover 71% of the housing stock.  However, small numbers of residential units (and even smaller numbers of commercial units) can have significant impact on the environment – we suggest that a similar use of area of deve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lopment footprint (for instance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> &gt; 0.5ha) might be a more effective </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">a priori </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">determinant of environmental impact.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A partially permissive approach may, in the long-term, come to work effectively, as planners and developers become convinced by the efficacy of offsetting in delivering sustainable development, but a partial approach reduces certainty, stifles supply markets and inhibits investment.  It is unlikely a coordinated national delivery system would emerg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> own analyses in the Impact A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssessment seem to prefer the partial approach only by dint of ignoring their own figures on the benefits to development. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Intelligent design – enabling not prescribing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Green Paper poses a number of questions about system design – offset location, restrictions, covenants, management agreements, registries, etc.  It is not the purpose of the EAC inquiry to replicate these questions but the Environment Bank would like to caution against ‘design by submission’ and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">offer a general view on overall design according to purpose.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘Making Space for Nature’ review</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> concluded that the existing network of protected sites was inadequate, that extra land was needed for nature </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">conservation management (‘more, bigger, better, joined’) and that biodiversity conservation was hugely underfunded. Offsetting funding is one potential, in fact probably the main, opportunity to address the Lawton review – offsetting funding is the private sector response to the environmental crisis, and takes conservation out of its current charitable and public sector niche. It is critical, however, that offsetting funding delivers environmental gain through land-use change, in other words starts to restore the highest quality semi-natural areas (and the lowest quality agricultural areas) back to sustainable conservation management. There are significant indications that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the agricultural industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is ready to do this.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The design of offsetting systems needs to enable this engagement by landowners and farmers across England, the following factors will help:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Land management contracts for offsetting supp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly at sensible scales (25 to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 99 years, not ‘in perpetuity’)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Farmer-friendly processes that encourage engagement</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Complementary interfaces with existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-environment schemes</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Costs that reflect real land management</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">No extra obligations placed on land used to deliver offsetting</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Appropriate rules in the offsetting metrics on, for instance, ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">additionality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’, scaling up with and between habitat types, and restoration/creation multipliers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Biodiversity offsetting is a new opportunity to make a difference to environmental conservation, and as such should not be designed with old-fashioned and restrictive mindsets.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Options for s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">pecies offsetting</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is little doubt that the planning system fails to deliver effective species conservation, particularly for the widespread but highly protected species – badgers, great crested newts, bats – that cause so much angst amongst planners and developers to so little conservation benefit.  The current system has two main fault-lines:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it is based on protection of individual animals rather than conservation of the species</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.71pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it focuses efforts and resources on distinguishing exact impact, rather than on changing outcomes – millions are spent on surveys instead of habitat creation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consequently, huge amounts of time and resources are expended discussing, and then protecting, a few individuals of a relatively common species.  The only beneficiaries of this system are the environmental consultants who service this industry, and the manufacturers of equipment (e.g. newt fencing) to do the same. The overall effect is counter-productive as developers are now increasingly reluctant to declare when protected species are discovered at a site.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Offsetting could certainly provide an effective alternative to the current system and the Environment Bank support the proposal in the Green Paper for species offsetting. In particular, we endorse the features that Defra set out th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> success</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> criteria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Respect for the mitigation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hierarchy (although we note</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, as with habitat offsetting, the issue of the ineffectiveness of many on-site mitigation proposals compared to off-site schemes)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59.66pt; padding-left:11.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A species-specific li</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ke-for-like approach that relies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on a much clearer and spatially-literate understanding of ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">favourable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> conservation status’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.71pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A ri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sk-based approach that delivers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> net gain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in outcomes, rather than focuses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on impacts.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In this context, we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recommend to Defra that a great </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">crested newt offsetting scheme be piloted in a part of the country where the constraints above can best be met.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Environment Bank welcomes the Defra Green Paper as an important step towards the introduction of offsetting in England.  If society is ever to ‘mainstream’ the value of the environment into its decision-making then there is a compelling need to introduce biodiversity offsetting on some mandatory basis.  We believe the Green Paper could have set out this case more strongly and that, as a result of the failure to do so, much of the arguments against offsetting will be poorly based.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.29pt; padding-left:15.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Offsetting in England should be an enabling instrument – one that allows better, quicker, more accurate and consistent, decisions to be made by planning authorities – to the benefit of both developers and the environment. As such, the Green paper should focus on general enabling, rather than on the detail of prescription or proscription.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">15 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">Hill, D. (2004</span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">).</span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt"> Mitigating Circumstances : What will we leave behind?</span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt"> IEE</span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">M Fellows Lecture</span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">. Proceedings of the 20</span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Cambria; font-size:6pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt"> Conference of the Institute of Ecology and Environmental Management. Ed. Rooney, P.</span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt"> et al</span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">. November 2004. IEEM.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">Tydesley</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:9pt">, D et al